Suddenly, the machine sprouted two metalic arms and started throwing pieces of cold, uncooked bacon across the room. One piece smacked Barnaby right in the forhead. "Hey! Stop that!" he yelled, waving his arms dramaticly. The birds chirping sound effect kicked in, but it was way to loud. It sounded more like a pterodactyl screaming in a cavern. Fluffles bolted under the sofa, wise enough to know when to seek cover.

Barnaby lunged for the "Off" switch, but his feet slipped on the blue oil. He went sliding across the floor like a penguin on ice. He crashed into a stack of old books, sending them flying everywhere. Even though he was coverred in oil and bacon, Barnaby couldn't help but laugh. "Well," he said, wiping a stray strip of meat off his glasses, "at least the ejection sistem works."

